                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/3890a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-07-05T18:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 5, 1922—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>164. Department is informed by Pacific Development Corporation that Chinese
                    Government is now negotiating with a Mr. Crisp of London for a loan under a
                    contract which provides for the payment of all Chinese Government’s indebtedness
                    to Americans and now in default including the Pacific Development loan. Does the
                    Legation know of any such negotiations? If so, what are the interests
                    represented by Mr. Crisp?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
